Hi guys, I've turned off my miners here, been mining for almost a year here. I'm focused on other things - don't take this as an opinion on the subnet, it's not. There should be a lot more spots on each model now. I suggest, as a miner, determining a low-cost way to do it rather than max competition. Value generation is important. Don't focus on the current token value, there's always room to grow.
Here's some stuff from my time mining:

• For my actual axon, these were all Google Cloud Platform. Why? Good edge node routing basically worldwide. Pick a central location (Texas), you'll have a fast connection to everyone.

• See above, but a lot of lowering your time is just optimizing connectivity, not speeding up generations.

• Cheating step count (months ago now) was a method of being fast for a certain amount of time, not too long. Prior to myself taking over most of the models, the current person did that. I did it too for a little bit. SN devs knew, reacted properly, tightened up similarity checks. It's still a little viable on some models (however, if someone is faster and doesn't do this, they will score higher), but for months now, including when I was building on each model to "take over," I've been running full step count on all. You don't need to cheat at all to be on top.

Just for an example of the above, take like AnimeV3, right - 24 steps is basically the same as 25 steps (passes almost every time), but over enough time and with enough volume, the person doing 25 steps would pass more similarity checks than the person doing 24, and therefore score higher, even if the person doing 24 is slightly faster. It was only a big issue when you could yolo 17 steps.

• GPUs have lots of VRAM, load multiple models in that VRAM to save money. Use a locking system to prevent those models from running simultaneously, as this generally causes a crash.

• I kept the main miner neuron portion of the code. This just sends requests to the generator anyway. No changes really needed.

• I rewrote all of the generator portion of the code with the above-mentioned locking system on H100 GPUs. These were able to load 5+ models into VRAM. Get rid of Ray entirely, never worked right for me. Instead, I started up a generator per GPU (so GPU 1 was port 2000, GPU 2 2001) and used Nginx to load balance to each GPU. Each generator could generate any of the models it had in VRAM. It created an endpoint for each one, i.e., /generate_rxl, generate_anime, etc. You can even copy-paste most of their generation_model/* files. Those are all fine, just the generator itself is slow and problematic.

• Well, why's it work when each one can only do 1 model at a time? Vali requests aren't exactly synchronized with each other. There's always some downtime for one model that can be used for another. I had between 48-64 of them at the peak, and then scaled down to more so around 40, and then an additional 24 4090s for the open category.

• The point of that system was to use H100s (expensive) but in a cost-effective way, not for a speed advantage. The card itself was that advantage.

• Use some sort of diffusion speed-up nonsense. There's a bunch of them and they don't affect similarity much.

• Slap gzip on your Nginx since Bittensor accepts gzip compressed automatically. Jon's idea, and I think he posted it here too.

• when taking over models/getting a lot of registrations in, its in your best interest to tank another model first, or balance the amount of emission that will be lost by each model. then, when the slower, bottom hotkeys of that model (which is likely to be the lowest emission model) are at the bottom of the miner list, register, and you've pushed out the slower competition. now someone else needs the capital to the same to you to get it back (this happened quite a few times too), eventually you should win that war of attrition

• I ran most of the miners on Rxl, Anime, Juggernaut, Kolors, Flux, and 75% of all the miners on every open category.
